1 Body length approximately 
<quantity box="[492,550,1692,1713]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="550" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
; wing with vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[725,746,1706,1718]" fontSize="5" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">2+3</subScript>
unusually short and veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1017,1038,1706,1718]" fontSize="5" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">4+5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1105,1112,1706,1718]" fontSize="5" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">1</subScript>
converging to nearly parallel apically (as in 
<figureCitation box="[341,430,1724,1745]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1164,1187]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,195,1142]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,193,1143]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 3–4. Photographs of male wings. 3. Hurleyella belizensis sp. nov.; 4. Hurleyella salina sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601774/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
); palpus and fore tarsus unmodified; wing without median fuscous band; hypopygium without distinct projections from one side; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Runyon &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="2010" box="[482,585,1753,1775]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hurleyella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[482,585,1753,1775]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Hurleyella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
...................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1692,2014]" box="[151,1435,1783,1804]" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1783,1804]" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
- Without above combination of characters.................................................. other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[1282,1435,1783,1804]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dolichopodidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1692,2014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
2 Coxa I mostly yellow; face and frons covered with dense silver pruinosity (
<figureCitation box="[956,1015,1812,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1038,1061]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,555,1017]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,555,1017]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Photographs of male heads, anterior view. 5. Hurleyella belizensis sp. nov.; 6. Hurleyella salina sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601776/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); wing with vein M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1208,1215,1825,1837]" fontSize="5" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">1</subScript>
arching greatly anteriorly on apical half (
<figureCitation box="[411,470,1844,1865]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1164,1187]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,195,1142]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,193,1143]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 3–4. Photographs of male wings. 3. Hurleyella belizensis sp. nov.; 4. Hurleyella salina sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601774/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); halter bright yellow (
<figureCitation box="[688,747,1844,1865]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="1.[151,264,634,657]" captionTargetBox="[192,1394,198,606]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[192,1394,195,610]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Habitus photographs of male holotypes. 1. Hurleyella belizensis sp. nov.; 2. Hurleyella salina sp. nov. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601772/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); hypandrium nearly symmetrical, hood-like (
<figureCitation box="[1186,1285,1844,1865]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–10" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1843,1866]" captionTargetBox="[153,1396,188,1825]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,188,1828]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–10. Hurleyella salina sp. nov., male terminalia. 9. ventral view; 10. left lateral view. Color codes of structures: light brown—epandrium; red—hypandrium; green—phallus + sperm pump + ejaculatory apodeme; blue—surstylus; orangebacilliform sclerite; purple—subepandrial sclerite; dark gray—abdominal sternite 8 and tergite 7. Abbreviations: epandepandrium; epd lobe—epandrial lobe; fsur—lateroapical flange of surstylus; hf—hypopygial foramen; hypd—hypandrium; hyprct—hypoproct; left v epand lb—left ventral lobe of epandrium; right v epand lb—right ventral lobe of epandrium; sbepand scl—subepandrial sclerite; S—abdominal sternite; T—abdominal tergite. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601780/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Figs 9, 10</figureCitation>
); alkali habitats (
<figureCitation box="[231,341,1873,1894]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–20" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1668,1691]" captionTargetBox="[181,1402,224,1647]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[181,1405,193,1648]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15–20. Collection localities and habitats of Hurleyella salina sp. nov. 15, 16. Type locality of H. salina sp. nov. at Deadman’s Basin, Montana, USA (46°20.53′N 109°22.94′W); 16. Specimens of H. salina sp. nov. were found at Deadman’s Basin in areas with lots of salt, mud cracks, and a little moisture; 17. Specimens were collected at Piedmont Pond, Montana, USA (45°50.634′N 112°06.848′W) on mostly dry soil with scattered grasses and a little crusted salt; 18. At Gyp Springs in south central Montana, USA (45°00.36′N 108°25.80′W), specimens were found on bare soil along lower wall of small canyon where water evaporates and salt forms (left center); 19. At Salt Creek in west central Wyoming, USA (42°28.00′N 110°58.07′W), H. salina sp. nov. was taken from areas near the creek with lots of salt (lower left); 20. At Fall Creek in eastern Idaho, USA (43°25.48′N 111°24.86′W), specimens were found on dry part of a travertine mound formed by cold mineral springs with evidence of some salt and other minerals." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601784/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Figs 15–20</figureCitation>
) (
<collectingRegion box="[361,419,1873,1894]" country="United States of America" name="Idaho" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Idaho</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[428,516,1873,1894]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Montana</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[526,623,1873,1894]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
).................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Runyon, 2019" authorityName="Runyon" authorityYear="2019" box="[1265,1353,1873,1895]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hurleyella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salina" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1265,1353,1873,1895]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">H. salina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,1873,1895]" pageId="2" pageNumber="550">
